**The Jade Chamber Secret Teachings** states:
The Yellow Emperor asked, “I wish to know the effects of movement without release.”
The Plain Girl replied:
“One movement without release strengthens qi and vigor;
Two movements without release sharpen hearing and vision;
Three movements without release dispel illness;
Four movements without release stabilize spirit and might;
Five movements without release replenish blood and vessels;
Six movements without release fortify the waist and back;
Seven movements without release enhance the buttocks and thighs;
Eight movements without release illuminate the body;
Nine movements without release extend lifespan without end;
Ten movements without release unite with the divine.”

**Nineteenth Chapter: Release and Ejaculation**
**The Jade Chamber Secret Teachings** states:
The Yellow Emperor asked the Plain Girl, “The essential Dao teaches not to lose essence, and one should cherish the fluids. Yet if one seeks offspring, how can ejaculation be permitted?”
The Plain Girl replied, “People vary in strength, and age differs in vitality. Each should follow their own qi and vigor, avoiding forced haste, for haste brings harm.
Thus, at fifteen, the robust may ejaculate twice daily, the frail once daily;
At twenty, the robust twice daily, the weak once daily;
At thirty, the robust once daily, the feeble once every two days;
At forty, the robust once every three days, the depleted once every four days;
At fifty, the robust once every five days, the weak once every ten days;
At sixty, the robust once every eleven days, the weak once every twenty days;
At seventy, the robust may ejaculate once every thirty days, the weak should not release.”

**Twentieth Chapter: Treating Injuries**

The *Secret Essentials of the Jade Chamber* states: The Plain Girl asked, “How can one gauge the rise and decline of a man’s vigor?”

Peng Zu replied, “When yang flourishes and qi is abundant, the jade stalk becomes hot, and the yang essence thickens and congeals. There are five signs of decline:
First, if essence spills out, qi is injured;
Second, if essence is thin and scant, the flesh is injured;
Third, if essence changes and turns foul, the sinews are injured;
Fourth, if essence flows out without forceful emission, the bones are injured;
Fifth, if the yin withers and fails to rise, the body itself is injured.
All these injuries stem from hasty and violent ejaculation rather than gradual union.

The remedy is to engage in intercourse without ejaculating. Within a hundred days, one’s qi and strength will surely increase a hundredfold.”

**Twenty-First Chapter: Seeking Offspring**

The *Secret Essentials of the Jade Chamber* states: The Plain Girl said, “The method for seeking offspring follows a constant pattern. Calm the mind, dispel distractions, and stabilize one’s resolve. Observe fasting and abstinence. On the third night after a woman’s menstrual flow, after midnight and before cock’s crow, play and arouse her so that her desire peaks, then proceed to unite. Follow the proper way, share in her pleasure, withdraw, and ejaculate. Deposit the essence half an inch from the jade gate—do not surpass the womb. As the *Thousand Wings* states, do not go too deep, only as far as the wheat-teeth. If too far, it will pass the child’s gate and fail to enter the child’s chamber. If one adheres to this Daoist art, the child will be virtuous, and both parents will enjoy longevity.”

It further states: The Plain Girl said, “When a man and woman unite in yin and yang, they must avoid taboos and always ride the qi of life. Then there is no one who will not live long. But if both husband and wife are aged, even if they conceive and bear a child, the child will not live long.”

**Twenty-Second Chapter: The Excellent Woman**

